# Architecture plan for Issue #131: Collapse long messages with an expand ("… more") control

## Module structure, file organization, shared types
- `frontend/src/App.tsx` renders the unified network chat feed and currently outputs message text inline in each chat card. The new `ExpandableMessageBody` React component should live in this file near the chat feed/message helpers because the behavior is local UI state only.
- `frontend/src/styles.css` owns the Tailwind component-layer styles for chat message text. Add `.tlhn-message-expand-button` there so the new control matches the TLHN terminal/neon visual system.
- `shared/src/*`, `backend/src/*`, database migrations, and API DTOs are out of scope: message bodies are already persisted and limited by existing contracts; this issue only changes presentation of already-fetched text.

## Dependencies between issues
- Issue #131 has no blocking dependencies.
- It builds on the existing combined feed and message composer, preserving the current 1000-character composer limit and server validation.

## Key design decisions
- Use a 256-character threshold exactly as requested. Bodies at or below the threshold render as plain full text; longer bodies render a truncated prefix plus a keyboard-accessible `… more` button.
- Keep expansion state per rendered message body using local component state; no persistence, API calls, or global state are needed.
- Preserve existing chat card layout, faction coloring, timestamps, scrolling, pagination, and relative time behavior.
- Validate with the frontend build/typecheck and, when available, the root build.
